# Adversary fixture: FM3-N3 — `=>` (log:implies) emits a triple with log:implies as predicate
#
# Hypothesis: The `=>` operator in N3 is syntactic sugar for the predicate
# `log:implies` (<http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/log#implies>). The statement
#
#   { :s :p :o } => { :s :q :r } .
#
# must produce exactly one triple whose predicate is
# `<http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/log#implies>`, with the two quoted
# formulas as subject and object respectively. A parser that:
#   (a) evaluates the implication rather than emitting the triple, or
#   (b) uses a different predicate URI for `=>`, or
#   (c) emits both inner triples into the default graph (treating `{}` as
#       a TriG-like named graph and flattening), or
#   (d) rejects `=>` entirely as unsupported syntax,
# will diverge against a conformant N3 parser.
#
# Expected: parse succeeds; exactly 1 triple in the default (ambient) graph,
# with predicate `log:implies`. The subject and object are quoted formulas
# (opaque values from the default-graph perspective).
#
# N3 spec §6: `expr1 => expr2` is shorthand for
#   `expr1 log:implies expr2 .`
# N3 spec §4: Each `{ ... }` is a formula node (cited graph).
#
# Divergence signal: AcceptRejectSplit (parser rejects `=>`), or
# PredicateMismatch (wrong predicate IRI emitted), or ExtraFactIn (inner
# triples leaked to default graph).
#
# Spec: W3C N3 Team Submission 2011-03-28 §6 — Implication; §4 — Formulae.

@prefix :    <http://example.org/> .
@prefix log: <http://www.w3.org/2000/10/swap/log#> .

{ :s :p :o } => { :s :q :r } .
